===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{label|en|intransitive}} To be saturated with liquid by being immersed in it.
#: {{ux|en|I'm going to '''soak''' in the bath for a couple of hours.}}
#* Bible, {{w|Book of Isaiah|Isaiah}} xxiv. 7
#*: Their land shall be '''soaked''' with blood.
# {{label|en|transitive}} To [[immerse]] in [[liquid]] to the point of saturation or thorough permeation.
#: {{ux|en|'''Soak''' the beans overnight before cooking.}}
# {{label|en|intransitive}} To [[penetrate]] or [[permeate]] by saturation.
#: {{ux|en|The water '''soaked''' into my shoes and gave me wet feet.}}
#* Sir {{w|Walter Scott}} (1771-1832)
#*: The rivulet beneath '''soaked''' its way obscurely through wreaths of snow.
# {{label|en|transitive}} To allow (especially a liquid) to be absorbed; to take in, receive. (''usually + '''[[up]]''''')
#: {{ux|en|A sponge '''soaks''' up water; the skin '''soaks''' in moisture.}}
#: {{ux|en|I '''soaked''' up all the knowledge I could at university.}}
#*{{quote-book|year=1927|author=[http://openlibrary.org/authors/OL2416183A F. E. Penny]
|chapter=4|title=[http://openlibrary.org/works/OL16814587W Pulling the Strings]
|passage=The case was that of a murder. It had an element of mystery about it, however, which was puzzling the authorities. A turban and loincloth '''soaked''' in blood had been found; also a staff.}}
# {{label|en|slang|dated}} To [[drink]] [[intemperate]]ly or [[gluttonous]]ly.
# {{label|en|metallurgy}} To heat a metal before shaping it.
# {{label|en|ceramics|}} To hold a kiln at a particular temperature for a given period of time.
#: {{ux|en|We should '''soak''' the kiln at cone 9 for half an hour.}}
# {{label|en|figurative}} To [[absorb]]; to [[drain]].
#: {{rfquotek|Sir H. Wotton}}

